            <h4><strong>Introduction</strong></h4>
            <p>
                Most students wonder what class they're likely to get for their <a href="https://www.open.ac.uk/"> Open University</a> degree, but many find the OU official guidance document, 
                <em><a href="https://help.open.ac.uk/documents/policies/working-out-your-class-of-honours/files/50/honours-class-working-out.pdf">Working Out Your Class of Honours</a></em> a little hard to follow.                
            </p>
            <p>
                This calculator is an attempt to help predict your degree class based on the modules you've completed and grades you're likley to get in future modules, made by an OU graduate who has been there! Thank you also to the popular but now sadly defunct
                <a href="http://cleveret.net/?page_id=29">Cleveret</a> calculator for inspiring this version. 
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Please be aware that this tool is completely unofficial, and provides an estimate only for informational purposes</strong>. 
                <br/>It has various limitations; it will not for example check that the modules entered can be counted towards your named degree or that any required modules have been added, or any other individual circumstances.
                Every effort has been made to ensure its accuracy, but responsibility can't be taken for wrong results, especially for less standard circumstances such as transferred credit. 
                <strong>Always <i>always</i> consult the official document from the Open University, or contact Student Support to discuss your individual qualification and likely result if in any doubt.</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Please <a href="@Email">email me</a> with any questions or suggestions and I'll do my best to help. If you roll that way, you can find the code on the
                <a href="https://github.com/LucyParry/degree-class-estimator/tree/master/src">GitHub repo</a> or just look at my cats on <a href="@Insta">Instagram</a>.
            </p>
