        <div class="mb-5">
            <h4><strong>How do UK undergraduate honours degrees work?</strong></h4>
            <p>
                The OU uses the same classification system as most other
                
                Most UK universities, including the <a href="https://www.open.ac.uk/"> Open University</a>, award degrees 'with honours' with one of four classifications. From highest to lowest,
                these are: first, upper second (2:1), lower second (2:2) and third. Degrees can also be awarded without honours, these are usually referred to as 'ordinary degrees' and do not receive a classification.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-5">
            <h4><strong>How is the degree class calculated for OU honours degrees?</strong></h4>
            <p>Every OU module is worth a fixed amount of credits, and an OU honours degree usually consists of 360 module credits in total.</p>
            <ul>
                <li class="mb-2"><strong>At least 240 of the credits must be at level 2 or above.</strong> Usually the grades from the modules making up these credits determine the degree class, although it can be less if transferred credit is used.</li>
                <li class="mb-2"><strong>At least 120 credits must be at level 3.</strong></li>
                <li class="mb-2">Credits at Level 1 count towards the total 360, but Level 1 grades <i>do not</i> count towards the degree class calculation.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The classification is then calculated in several steps -</p>
            <ol>
                <li class="mb-2">
                    The highest graded 120 module credits at level 3 are taken first. Each of these modules is given a graded score based on the credits multiplied by a number given corresponding to the grade. A Distinction = 1, Grade 2 = 2, etc.
                    A grade of Pass 3 on <em><a href="https://www.open.ac.uk/courses/modules/tm354">TM354 - Software engineering</a></em> for example, would have a graded score of 90 (30 credits x 3 for Pass 3). 
                </li>

                <li class="mb-2">
                    These graded scores are then multiplied by 2 to give them double weighting in the final calculation. In TM354 example above, we would have a final weighted and graded score of 180 (90 x 2).
                </li>

                <li class="mb-2">
                    Any remaining elligible modules, which are usually the 120 credits at level 2, are then also given a graded score using the same method in step 1 of credits multiplied by grade, but these are <em>not</em> then given the double weighting.
                    A Pass 2 on <em><a href="https://www.open.ac.uk/courses/modules/a222">Exploring philosophy</a></em> for example would be given 120 (60 credits x 2 for Pass 2).
                </li>
                <li class="mb-2">
                    The scores for each module calculated in this way are then summed up, and the total determines the <strong>initial</strong> degree classification. Usually, the grade thresholds are as below (although this can be different for degrees with transferred credit) -
                    <br/><br/>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-hover table-bordered table-responsive-sm5 m-2">
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">First</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">630 or less</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Upper Second (2:1)</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">631 to 900</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Lower Second (2:2)</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">901 to 1170</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Third</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">1171 to 1440</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <br/>
                </li>

                <li class="mb-2">
                    After the initial classification is calculated, a 'quality assurance' check is done to make sure that the highest scoring 60 credits at level 3 meets or exceeds the initial classification. 
                    This usually uses the following thresholds (again note that degrees with transferred credit differ) -
                    <br/><br/>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-hover table-bordered table-responsive-sm5 m-2">
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">First</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">At least 60 credits with Distinction grade</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Upper Second (2:1)</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Graded credit between 61 and 120 </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Lower Second (2:2)</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Graded credit between 121 and 180</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Third</td>
                                <td style="width: 50%;">Graded credit between 181 and 240</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <br/>
                </li>

                <li class="mb-2">
                    If the quality assurance classification is the same or better than the initial classification calculated in step 4, you should be awarded the initial classification for your degree. If the quality
                    assurance classification is lower than the initial classification though, you'll be awarded the lower quality assurance classification.
                </li>
            </ol>

